  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses 9% growth and a 9% discount rate. Here's how the intrinsic value fluctuates under varying assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is perfectly complete. Here are the subjective risks and upside potential our math doesn't measure.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Streaming Dominance:</strong> If Disney+ margins achieve Netflix-like efficiency, FCF growth will massively exceed 9%.</li>
    <li><strong>Parks Expansion:</strong> New land expansions and cruise ships could provide a strong revenue bump that extends beyond 5 years.</li>
    <li><strong>Epic Games Partnership:</strong> Successful monetization of Disney IP within Fortnite and the gaming space could open an entirely new, high-margin revenue stream.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Linear TV Collapse:</strong> If the traditional cable bundle (ESPN, ABC) deteriorates faster than streaming grows, total cash flows could temporarily shrink.</li>
    <li><strong>Studio Missteps:</strong> Theatrical releases carry high variance. Continued underperformance from Marvel or Pixar would severely impact profitability.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> Disney has over $42 billion in debt. Rising interest rates for refinancing could pressure net income and limit share buybacks.</li>
  </ul>

